art focus lecture paul klee a swiss enigma events at stanford art focus lecture paul klee a swiss enigma facebook twitter email print add to calendar wednesday february 29 since 1987 the san francisco museum of modern art has featured a gallery devoted to the work of paul klee these works on paper from the collection of dr carl djerassi allow viewers an intimate look at the enigmatic artist whose work continues to charm and inspire museum visitors the drawings paintings and prints have led to an ongoing series of exhibitions that allow curators to renew the many approaches to the work of klee and his continuing significance this lecture will highlight exhibitions of the collection and the many histories they illuminate john zarobell is assistant professor and program chair in european studies at the university of san francisco and formerly assistant curator of painting and sculpture at the san francisco museum of modern art he acted as the coordinating curator of frida kahlo and also organized art in the atrium kerry james marshall as well as a series of paul klee exhibitions at sfmoma he contributes to the web based journal art practical and has published in art history and nineteenth centuryart worldwide his book empire of landscape was published in january 2010 he has taught at uc berkeley stanford university and tulane university when wednesday february 29 2012 4 15 pm approximate duration of 2 hour s where cantor arts center auditorium map audience general public faculty staff students alumni friends members tags arts lecture reading visual sponsor cantor arts center contact 723 3482 admission cantor arts center member $25 non member $30 drop in attendance is offered for $30 on the day of a lecture if space is available no advance reservations are possible for drop in payment by check or cash accepted at the door permalink http events stanford edu events 303 30341 more info last modified february 27 2012
